    <title>Supplementary data</title>
    <p id="p0475">The following are the Supplementary data to this article:<supplementary-material content-type="local-data" id="m0005"><caption><title>Supplementary data 1</title></caption><media xlink:href="mmc1.pdf"/></supplementary-material></p>
  </sec>
  <fn-group>
    <fn id="fn1">
      <label>1</label>
      <p id="np010">The term binge-watching co-exists with the more comprehensive and stigma-free concept of media-marathoning (<xref rid="b0085" ref-type="bibr">Perks, 2015</xref>:ix) that emphasizes viewers’ engagement with a narrative world and viewers’ agency to decide upon the duration of a narrative journey.</p>
    </fn>
    <fn id="fn2">
      <label>2</label>
      <p id="np015">See: <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/1107559/video-streaming-consumption-growth-worldwide-coronavirus/" id="ir005"><underline>https://www.statista.com/statistics/1107559/video-streaming-consumption-growth-worldwide-coronavirus/</underline></ext-link>.</p>
    </fn>
    <fn id="fn3">
      <label>3</label>
      <p id="np020">To have an overview of what previous researchers have done, we used the literature review conducted by <xref rid="b0070" ref-type="bibr">Merikivi, Bragge, Scornavacca, and Verhagen (2019)</xref> as a starting point, which we updated with the academic literature published until May 2020.</p>
    </fn>
    <fn id="fn4">
      <label>4</label>
      <p id="np025">BWDAT follows the aim of the B-Watch tool, described by (<xref rid="b9010" ref-type="bibr">Cabral et al., 2020</xref>) but with a new sustainable and dynamic approach. The open code, the open access URL to the tool and the manual to use it, are all available in the following link: <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://github.com/JoseDAssisCordeiro/BWDAT" id="ir010">https://github.com/JoseDAssisCordeiro/BWDAT</ext-link>.</p>
    </fn>
    <fn id="fn5">
      <label>5</label>
      <p id="np030">The most commonly used browser in the web (63.8%): <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://www.w3counter.com/globalstats.php" id="ir015"><underline>https://www.w3counter.com/globalstats.php</underline></ext-link>, visited on the 23rd November 2020.</p>
    </fn>
    <fn id="fn6">
      <label>6</label>
      <p id="np035">A session is defined as the time between the opening of a Netflix tab and its closure.</p>
    </fn>
    <fn id="fn7">
      <label>7</label>
      <p id="np040">We evaluated several devices combining reliability, cost, ease of development and autonomy, and compatibility with Wear OS 2.0 (<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://wearos.google.com" id="ir020">https://wearos.google.com</ext-link>) operating system, which allows for standalone applications. The Polar m600 smartwatch Android-based wearable was selected. A technical test was run with Polar m600, by comparing the data collected from 4 users with Empatica E4, giving an average mean absolute error of 5.31%. According to <xref rid="b0075" ref-type="bibr">Nelson and Allen (2019)</xref>, an average absolute error below 10% serves as an indicator of an acceptable heart rate accuracy.</p>
    </fn>
